Learning objectives

  • Apply poisson and negative binomial regression models to count data
  • Identify and apply suitable model to overdispersed data
  • Identify influential observations
  • Perform model diagnostics

1 Overdispersion

  • In many situations, we find that count data have a particular property which makes the Poisson model unsuitable for use the variance of our count data is appreciably larger than the mean, this is known as overdispersion.

  • We can generalise the Poisson regression model to include a random effect i in the rate

    • Introduce some uncertainty into the model > larger variance
    • We can think of i as representing the effects of one or more unobserved explanatory variables

  • In the special case where we allow exp(i) to follow a gamma distribution with mean 1 and variance , then Yi follows a negative binomial distribution wiki with

    • Mean = i
    • Variance = i + i2
      • Variance always greater than mean (coz i2 is a non-negative part)
      • Larger , larger variance
    • When we try to fit regression model for count data, we start with negative binomial model instead of poisson model and check whether alpha close to 0.
    ## rpois(10000,5): generate 10000 number following poisson distribution with mean = 5
mean(rpois(10000,5))
var(rpois(10000,5))

## Generate negative binomial distribution with random effect following gamma mean=1, variance=2
# mean = k; variance = k^2
# shape k; rate  = 1/
mean(rpois(10000, 5*rgamma(10000,1/2,1/2)))
var(rpois(10000, 5*rgamma(10000,1/2,1/2))) #larger variance, suitable to describe count
#data with overdispersion

supplementary info

Example Epileptic seizures

  • The file exampleepilepsy.csv contains data from a RCT which compared progabide (therapy=1) with a placebo (therapy=0)

  • For each patient we know:

    • the number of seizures (x) experienced in 8 weeks prior to randomisation
    • the number of seizures (y) experienced during the 8-week trial (lets set A = 1 since all patients had the same follow-up)
    • We also know each patients age

  • Was progabide more effective than placebo in reducing seizure frequency?

    epilepsy <- read.csv("Folder/exampleepilepsy.csv")

deviance(pois.epilepsy)/df.residual(pois.epilepsy) #much greater than 1

1.2 Fitting NegBin model

  • Unfortunately, the glm function in R only fits negative binomial regression model when is known.
  • For the case when is unknown and has to be estimated from the parameter, use glm.nb in the MASS (Modern Applied Statistics) package
    • glm.nb(formula, data, subset, )
      • formula, data and subset same as glm
      • family not needed
require(MASS)
## Fit a NegBin regression model
nb.epilepsy0 <- glm.nb(y~1, data=epilepsy)
summary(nb.epilepsy0)

1.3 Comparing models

  • We can compare models based on the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), which is defined as AIC = 2k 2ln(L)
    • where k is the number of parameters in the model, L is the likelihood
      • To count number of parameter(k/df): each model includes an intercept term 0, scale parameter and explanatory variables.
    • A lower AIC indicates a better model
    • As a rule of thumb, a difference >= 2 is significant
    AIC(nb.epilepsy0, nb.therapy1, nb.therapy2, nb.therapy3)
    ##              df      AIC
## nb.epilepsy0  2 507.1881
## nb.therapy1   3 505.8973
## nb.therapy2   5 462.8663
## nb.therapy3   5 455.6771
    # From the above table we conclude that the AIC favors Model 3.
Conclusions from epilepsy example data
  • We can present the adjusted relative risk of seizures for progabide compared to placebo, which is 0.74 (95% CI: 0.55-0.98)
    • We can say that the seizure rate varies a great deal between patients
  • We have seen that the log-transformed baseline seizure rate is a more useful explanatory variable than the original seizure rate (model 3)
    • The fit of the NegBin model seems to be acceptable

2 Influential observations

  1. Leverage
    • How much an observation differs from the mean of the predictor variables (i.e., unusual predictor values, left figure)
  2. Cooks distance
    • Change in predicted values if an observation were excluded (right figure)

2.1 Leverage

  • Leverage values are often used for detecting observations that have a large impact on the predicted values
    • hatvalues(model)
    • Bounded by 0 and 1
    • Average value of leverage values = k/n
      • k: number of estimated parameters in the model, including the constant/intercept
      • n: sample size
    • Rough guideline: observations with values > 2k/n are influential
      • In the MVC example (MVC = + 1age + 2height), 2k/n = 2 3 / 41 = 0.1463
    mvc <- read.csv("Folder/mvc.csv")
mvc.r <- mvc
mvc.r$height[41] <- 178 #create 1 single influential observation
mvc.r.lm <- lm(MVC ~ height + age, data=mvc.r)
sort(hatvalues(mvc.r.lm), decreasing=T) #Calculate leverage statistics

2.2 Cooks distance (Di)

  • A measure of the overall influence of a case on a model as a whole. How much deleting an observation will affect the model
    • cooks.distance(model)
    • Tells us how much deleting a case affects not only the residual for that case, but also the residuals of the remaining cases (fyi)
    • Cooks distance depends on the standardized residuals of a case and its leverage.(fyi)
      • \(D_i = \frac{Z^2_i \times h_i}{(1-h_i)k}\)
      • where Zi is the standardized residual, hi is the leverage, k is the number of parameters
    • Rough guideline: observations with Di > 4/n are influential
      • In the MVC example, 4/n = 4 / 41 = 0.0976
    sort(round(cooks.distance(mvc.r.lm),2), decreasing=T) #Calculate Cooks distance
    ##   41    5    8   37   21    1   13   33   40    7    9   14    2   17   26   32

What to do?

Dont throw away data easily without justification

  1. Check if theres any typo (reassess if the data came from the target population)
  2. Perform sensitivity analysis
    • Do the analysis again excluding influential observations
    • Do the results change qualitatively if we remove the outliers?

3 Model diagnostics

Why model diagnostics?

  • Estimation method and statistical tests are based on model assumptions.General consequences of violated assumptions: a) Biased estimated coefficients or standard errors b) Inefficient estimation (achieving lower precision with the same sample size)
  • Model diagnostics: Identify any potential violated assumptions. If yes, assess the extent of violation. Acknowledge limitation of the fitted model Or suggest an alternative statistical model if assumptions seriously violated

3.1 Assumptions of linear regression model

  1. Linearity: Linear relationship between predictors(x) and dependent variable (y)
  2. Constant variance of the errors (Homoscedasticity) (spread of bell shaped curve is constant)
  3. Normality of the errors (bell shaped curve)
  4. Independence: No correlation / autocorrelation between the errors
  • The last three assumptions can be summarized as \( iid ~ N(0, 2)\) where iid = independently and identically distributed
  • Use Residual plot to identify violation of assumptions
    • Raw residual: Difference between observed outcome and estimated valuemodel$res
      • \(e=y-\widehat{y}\)
    • Studentized residuals: Standardized residuals by each data point rstudent(model)
      • \(r_i=\frac{e_i}{\widehat\sigma\sqrt{1-h_i}}\)
      • If model assumptions are correct, studentized residuals will follow a t-distribution with mean = 0 and variance = 1

A Nonlinearity

Plot studentized residuals against each predictor (x)

  • Non-linear pattern suggests higher order terms or transformations of that predictor may be necessary
  • Less useful for categorical variables (e.g., age grp 123)

plot(x, residual)

C Non-normality of the errors

i Residual plot by observations

Plot studentized residuals, see if errors are normally distributed. Errors

  • Should be symmetrically distributed with mean 0 and variance 1
  • Should have around 5% of the absolute studentized residuals exceeding 2

plot(residual) abline(h=c(0,-2,2))

plot(stresid.mvc, ylim=c(-2.5,2.5))
abline(h=c(0,-2,2), lty=2)

# 2/41 ~ 5% studentized residuals fall outside the range [-2, 2] so the model is true

ii pp lot / qq plot

Normal probability plot (p-p plot) / Normal quantile plot (q-q plot) of residuals

  • If two variables have the same distribution (plotting dataset against normal distribution), points should fall on the 45 line on a p-p or q-q plot
  • p-p plot more sensitive to deviation from normality in the middle range; q-q plot more sensitive to outer range

qqnorm(residual) abline(0,1)

## Q-Q plot
qqnorm(stresid.mvc)
abline(0,1) #no severe deviation from normality

## P-P plot (not teached in lecture)
pd.stresid.mvc <- pnorm(stresid.mvc)
plot(ppoints(length(stresid.mvc)), sort(pd.stresid.mvc), main = "PP
Plot", xlab = "Observed Probability", ylab = "Expected Probability")
abline(0,1) #no severe deviation from normality

D Non-independence of the errors

  • Non-independence = serial correlation/autocorrelation
    • Sometimes a by-product of misspecification of the time trend when time is a predictor in the model

i Residual plot by observations

  • Plot studentized residuals over time
    • Adjacent errors tend to have the same sign if errors are serially correlated
    • Note: Meaningful only if observations were made sequentially

plot(residual)

plot(stresid.mvc, xlab='observation number') # No obvious autocorrelation in the residuals

ii ACF plot

ACF: autocorrelation function

  • Correlation between the same variable at different time point
  • Xt = variable X observed at time t
    • If ACF/PACF exceed threshold/confidence limit in the first few lags > autocorrelation
    • Correlation for time lag 0 is def 1 coz we are comparing varaibles at same time interval
    • PACF: partial ACF remove effect from other time lags (indirect correlation)

acf(residual) pacf(residual)

1 time lag 

acf(stresid.mvc) #No obvious correlation in the residuals

pacf(stresid.mvc) #No obvious correlation in the residuals

3.2 Assumptions of other models glm

  1. Linearity
    Linear relationship between predictors and dependent variable through a smooth invertible link function
  2. Errors can follow a distribution from the exponential family (e.g.Normal, Bernoulli, Poisson)
  3. Independence
    No correlation / autocorrelation between the errors

Model diagnostics for glm

  • Crude residuals are not used coz variance depends on mean
  • Deviance residuals can be used glm.model$res
    • A measure of deviation from the likelihood of a saturated model (fit in the model to data with no. of parameters = no. of data points)
  • Studentized deviance residuals can be obtained by rstudent(glm.model) follow a standard normal distribution if the model is correctly specified
